  "prompt": "Why is Chicago called the \"City of Broad Shoulders\"?",
  "response": "The phrase \"City of Broad Shoulders\" comes from a line in Carl Sandburg's 1916 poem \"Chicago,\" which celebrates the city's industrial might, hard-working laborers, and resilient spirit. The full line reads: \"They tell me you are wicked and I believe them, for I have seen your painted women under the gas lamps luring the farm boys. And they tell me you are crooked and I answer: Yes, it is true I have seen the gunman kill and go free to kill again.\" The \"broad shoulders\" metaphorically represent the strength, toughness, and industrial power of Chicago and its workers during the early 20th century, when the city was a major industrial and manufacturing center.",
